  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Statement.}\nClassical emergence occurs when decoherence suppresses interference and pointer states evolve according to effective classical equations derived from the Trawinistic Hamiltonian.\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Condition.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\rho_{ij}(t)\\rightarrow 0\n\\qquad\n(i\\neq j).\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $\\rho$ be a density matrix written in a pointer-state basis $\\{|i\\rangle\\}$.  \nThe off-diagonal entries\n\\begin{equation}\n\\rho_{ij}\n=\n\\langle i|\\rho|j\\rangle,\n\\qquad i\\neq j,\n\\end{equation}\nencode quantum interference between distinct pointer states.\n\nClassical behavior emerges when these off-diagonal terms decay rapidly:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\rho_{ij}(t)\\rightarrow 0\n\\qquad\n(i\\neq j).\n\\end{equation}\n\nThe remaining diagonal entries behave as an effective classical probability distribution:\n\\begin{equation}\np_i(t)=\\rho_{ii}(t).\n\\end{equation}\n\nThus the quantum state becomes approximately classical in the pointer basis:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\n\\rho(t)\n\\longrightarrow\n\\sum_i p_i(t)|i\\rangle\\langle i|.\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nClassical behavior is obtained when interference is suppressed and the pointer-state probabilities dominate the observable dynamics.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
